[normal]The replacement of council tax benefit with localised schemes has led to significant extra costs for people on low incomes, particularly in poorer areas[bold].[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]2.1.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]LHA caps combin[bold]ed [bold]with high demand for rental properties [bold]are[bold] likely to be[bold] mak[bold]ing [bold]people homeless[bold], especially in London. [bold]2.2.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]in April 2011 t
[normal]he Government introduced caps on the maximum amount of LHA, 
[normal]the
[normal] type of housing benefit that people living in private rented accommodation
[normal] claim
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Since these caps were introduced
[normal],
[normal] official
[normal] statistics
[normal] show a dramatic rise in the number of people who have become homeless after losing private rented accommodation
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]There has been a 78 per cent increase
[normal] in
[normal] the number of people becoming homeless due to the end of an assured shorthold tenancy
[normal], the most common type of private tenancy,
[normal] when the first quarter of 2013 is compared to the first quarter of 2011.
[normal] 
[normal]2.3.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Caps to LHA are likely to be partly responsible for t
[normal]his increase. 
[normal]Few l
[normal]andlords are lowering rents 
[normal]as the amount of housing benefit that their tenants can claim is capped. 
[normal]Department for Work and Pensions research shows that 37 per cent of private landlords 
[normal]in London 
[normal]have taken action to evict tenants or no
[normal]t renew tenancies when there is a shortfall between LHA and rent
[normal], 
[normal]while 
[normal]just 
[normal]6 
[normal]per 
[normal]would consider 
[normal]lower
[normal]ing
[normal] rent
[normal] for a current tenant
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]DWP research also
[normal] 
[normal]that landlords and housing advisors believe that the changes to LHA are behind increases in homelessnes
[normal]s.
[normal]2.4.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In
[normal] August
[normal] 2012 Hackney Citizens Advice 
[normal]found that just nine per cent of rental properties on the market
[normal] in Hackney
[normal] were within LHA limits for self contained accommodation. Ninety per cent of
[normal] 
[normal]properties within these limits were owned by landlords un
[normal]will
[normal]ing to
[normal] 
[normal]accept LHA claimants
[normal]. Therefore 
[normal]only one per cent of rental properties 
[normal]in Hackney were available to LHA claimants.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The annual cap of a
[normal] one 
[normal]per cent
[normal] increase to the LHA cap that will take effect from April 2014 will 
[normal]further reduce
[normal] the number of 
[normal]ren
[normal]tal properties available in London with LHA levels
[normal],
[normal] as rents look certain to rise
[normal] by more than 
[normal]one
[normal] per cent
[normal] a year.
[normal] 
[normal]The Government could mitigate this widening affordability gap through targeting LHA affordability funding at areas in London. 
[normal]2.6.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]If people can
[normal]not 
[normal]find affordable rented
[normal] accommodation then there is usually no other type of accomm
[normal]odation that they can rent or buy
[normal]. 
[normal]S
[normal]ome people m
[normal]ay cho
[normal]o
[normal]se to move
[normal] areas
[normal] with cheaper housing available. O
[normal]thers may try to remain within living distance of their work, 
[normal]family, friends or services that the
[normal]y
[normal] rely on such as schools
[normal] and medical care
