[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.1.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In St Mungo’s experience an ever greater proportion of the accommodation which is available within LHA rates is 
[normal]in 
[normal]poor
[normal] condition. 
[normal]T
[normal]enants 
[normal]often move into these properties
[normal] as they feel they have no 
[normal]choice
[normal] but do 
[normal]so,
[normal] hoping that repairs and maintenance work
[normal] will be completed by the landlord. Living in a poor quality property
[normal] can often
[normal] impact 
[normal]on tenant’s health and
[normal] lead
[normal]s
[normal] to an increased risk of homelessness.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4.1.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The introduction of the LHA caps has made it more difficult for St Mungo’s clients to move out of our projects and into private 
[normal]rented housing, especially in London. In the last two years there has been a steep decline in the number of our clients who have move
[normal]d
[normal] on from our projects into social housing. Over the same period the number of clients moving into private rented housing h
[normal]as ceased to grow.
[normal]4.2.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]We are concerned that this will mean an increasing number of our clients will be stuck in supported accommodation 
[normal]despite being
[normal] ready to live 
[normal]independently
[normal]. This is likely to cause our hostels to ‘silt up’, meaning we cannot 
[normal]provide beds
[normal] 
[normal]people who are sleeping rough.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]As landlords raise rent to levels not met by LHA, m
[normal]ore peo
[normal]ple who have been homeless 
[normal]but have since moved into private rented housing 
[normal]will have
[normal] to move at the end of a tenancy
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]When homeless they may have been assisted to move into private housing by a local au
[normal]thority or 
[normal]other service through contribution
[normal] towards
[normal] 
[normal]the deposit and 
[normal]rent 
[normal]advance
[normal]. However, this assistance is 
[normal]usually non transferable, meaning that at the end of 
[normal]the
[normal] initial 
[normal]tenancy the 
[normal]person
[normal] has no financial assistance 
[normal]to secure a new home. 
[normal]This leads to an increased risk of repeat homelessness
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]6.1.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]There is considerable uncertainty around the immediate and long term effects of welfare reform on the funding of supported accommodation. 
[normal]The 
[normal]Government consulted on the future of housing benefit and supported accommodation in 2011, but has yet to produce 
[normal]a response to the submissions it received. 
[normal]6.2.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In the meantime 
[normal]the 
[normal]Government has committed to retain current arrangements for meeting the housing costs of benefit claimants living in supported ‘exempt’ accommodation, i.e. housing benefit will be administered
[normal] by local authorities
[normal] and paid directly to the landlord.
[normal] 
[normal]However, the legal definition of ‘exempt’ accommodation does not cov
[normal]er all supported accommodation. It is likely that 
[normal]t
[normal]here are high support projects homelessness project
[normal]s
[normal] which may not meet the defi
[normal]nition.
[normal]6.3.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]People staying in supported accommodation that falls outside the definition (non exempt supported accommodation) will have support for their housing costs limited by the overall benefit cap. 
[normal]Th
[normal]is will make it difficult to meet the cost of running p
[normal]rojects designed for people with very high housing needs.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]I
[normal]t is
[normal] also
[normal] unclear how people
[normal] in these projects
[normal] will be able to claim any support whatsoever
[normal] through Universal Credit
[normal] for housing costs for stays in non exempt 
[normal]supported 
[normal]accommodation lasting less 
[normal]than a month.
[normal]6.4.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]St Mungo’s understand that this is a complex policy area which
[normal] the
[normal] 
[normal]G
[normal]overnment are working with partners
[normal] to resolve. A timely resolution 
[normal]is vital to enable 
[normal]providers of supported accommodation
[normal] 
[normal]to be able to plan for the future
[normal]. Failure to reso
[normal]lve these issues could 
[normal]reduce the
[normal] amount of accommodation available for people who are homeless as homelessness increases. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]7.1.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]St Mungo’s are implementing a strategy to boost the financial and budgeting skill
[normal]s of our clients. However, uncertainty over DWP’s plans around alternative payments and local support services mean it is extremely challenging to plan how the support we provide can be coordinated with Universal Credit.
